    {
      "id": "5be35d08b0d456f7b73bde0f121de57c31e81b13",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-08-11 16:35:33.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nI don't understand why there would be a valid case where rc != 0 with transno != 0 as well?  shouldn't this just return an error?\n\nWhat it also looks like the code will do is for cases where the transno is zero (e.g. lookup or other non-modifying operation) that the xid and rc will be updated, but the transno is left at the previous value, so if the client needs to resend the RPC at this point (after a lost reply) it will think hat this RPC with matching XID has been assigned a transno and keep it in the replay list.\n\nI though the code was structured to overwrite the last_rcvd client transno with 0 in this case, but if the client transno > transno in header then the header will be updated to avoid losing the highest last_committed transno? Maybe this is only being done in the OST code, or in b1_8?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "d6a8a2a61831cb054383709acc3b49d1d2925817",
